# Technical Design Guidelines

## General Philosophy

The application should be designed as a single coherent experience.

Avoid building independent pages or disconnected dashboard components.

Every section should feel like part of the same story.

The user should naturally progress from one section to the next.

Think:

Apple product pages.

Stripe annual reports.

Airbnb data storytelling.

Our World in Data.

The experience must feel intentional.

---

# Technical Architecture

## Single Page Application

Use a single-page architecture.

Do not create multiple pages.

Structure:

- Hero
- Energy Mix
- Global Map
- Country Comparison
- Diversification
- Conclusions

Navigation should scroll smoothly between sections.

The user should never feel lost.

---

# Data Architecture

## Load Data Once

The CSV must be loaded only once.

Create a centralized data layer.

Example:

data-loader.js

Responsibilities:

- Load CSV
- Clean data
- Normalize fuel categories
- Create derived metrics
- Expose processed dataset globally

Avoid loading or parsing the CSV multiple times.

---

## Create Aggregated Datasets

The raw dataset contains approximately 35,000 power plants.

Visualizations should not process raw data repeatedly.

Generate precomputed structures:

### Global Statistics

Used by Hero section.

Contains:

- totalPlants
- totalCountries
- totalCapacity
- totalFuelTypes

### Country Aggregation

Contains:

- country
- totalCapacity
- totalPlants
- renewableShare
- dominantFuel
- diversificationIndex

### Fuel Aggregation

Contains:

- fuel
- totalCapacity
- percentage

These structures should be generated once during initialization.

---

# Visual System

## Typography

Typography should carry the design.

Use:

Inter
or
SF Pro Display equivalent

Hierarchy:

Hero title:
64px+

Section title:
40px+

Body:
16-18px

Avoid decorative fonts.

---

## Layout

Use a fixed content width.

Example:

max-width: 1200px

Center all content.

Use generous spacing.

Recommended:

120px vertical spacing between sections.

The page should feel breathable.

---

## Color System

Use a restrained palette.

Neutral background:

#FAFAF8

Primary text:

#111111

Secondary text:

#666666

Use color only for fuel types.

Never use random chart colors.

Fuel color mapping must remain consistent everywhere.

Example:

Coal → Dark Gray

Gas → Blue

Hydro → Cyan

Solar → Yellow

Wind → Green

Nuclear → Purple

Biomass → Brown

This mapping must never change across visualizations.

---

# Animation Principles

## Subtle Motion

Animations should support understanding.

Never animate for decoration.

Good examples:

- KPI counting animation
- Fade-in sections
- Smooth map transitions
- Chart transitions

Bad examples:

- Flying elements
- Excessive parallax
- Bouncing cards

Motion should feel calm.

---

# Section 1 — Hero

## Technical Notes

Do not place charts here.

Only:

- Title
- Subtitle
- KPIs

The objective is establishing scale.

Add slight number animation when section becomes visible.

Use Intersection Observer.

---

# Section 2 — Treemap

## Technical Notes

Use D3 Treemap.

Important:

The treemap must show capacity.

Not plant count.

Capacity answers the research question better.

Tooltip:

- Fuel
- Total capacity
- Percentage

Interaction:

Click fuel

→ Filters map section automatically.

This creates continuity between sections.

---

# Section 3 — Global Map

## Technical Notes

This is the centerpiece.

Allocate the largest screen space here.

Preferred libraries:

MapLibre
or
Leaflet

Do not use Google Maps.

Performance:

35,000 points can be heavy.

Use:

- clustering
  or
- WebGL rendering

When zoomed out:

show clusters.

When zoomed in:

show individual plants.

This improves performance dramatically.

---

## Filters

Keep filters minimal.

Maximum:

- Fuel Type
- Capacity Range

Avoid excessive dropdowns.

Users should explore visually.

---

# Section 4 — Country Comparison

## Technical Notes

This section answers:

"Do countries generate electricity in the same way?"

Limit comparison to two countries.

Do not allow more.

Visualization:

100% stacked bar chart.

This is easier to understand than radar charts.

Display:

- Fuel composition
- Renewable share
- Total capacity

Everything should fit above the fold.

---

# Section 5 — Diversification

## Technical Notes

This section introduces a new insight.

Use Shannon Diversity Index.

Formula can remain hidden.

Show plain language explanation:

"A higher score means electricity is generated from a wider variety of energy sources."

Avoid academic language.

Visualization:

Horizontal ranking chart.

Not scatterplot.

Reason:

Users understand rankings immediately.

Show:

Top 20 most diversified countries.

This creates a much stronger story.

---

# Section 6 — Conclusions

## Technical Notes

No charts.

Only narrative.

Generate insight cards dynamically from data.

Examples:

Most diversified country.

Most renewable country.

Largest coal dependency.

Largest installed capacity.

Largest power plant.

Cards should feel editorial.

Think magazine summary.

---

# Accessibility

All visualizations must work with:

- keyboard navigation
- screen readers
- responsive layouts

Minimum contrast ratio:

WCAG AA

Never encode meaning using color alone.

Use labels and tooltips.

---

# Performance

Target:

Initial load < 3 seconds.

Strategies:

- Precompute aggregations
- Lazy load visualizations
- Debounce filters
- Cluster map points

The experience should feel instantaneous.

---

# Final Quality Check

Before considering the project complete, verify:

Every section answers one question.

Every visualization supports the story.

Every interaction has a purpose.

No chart exists solely because it looks interesting.

The user should finish the experience understanding the global electricity system, not merely browsing charts.
